  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Abstractly put, an argument for us is a sequence of formulae in some formal language of some logic or logics, where the sequence links these formulae by instances of inference schemata.",
    "A proof is an argument in which (i) the inference schemata in play are restricted to deductive ones, and (ii) some premises given in the sequence in question enjoy special status because they are members of a pre-identified axiom system (e.g., axioms for Euclidean geometry, or for arithmetic, or topology).",
    "MHP, as a matter of fact, in our formalization and solution, involves both likelihood and probability.",
    "Since the emphasis, herein, is very much on the former, we do not bring to bear our full formalization and implementation of the probability calculus of Kolmogorov within a richer version of IDCEC.",
    "Doing so would be overkill in the present study, since the key manner of handling uncertainty is here cognitive likelihood not probability."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Since the emphasis, herein, is very much on the former, we do not bring to bear our full formalization and implementation of the probability calculus of Kolmogorov within a richer version of IDCEC."
